result.execSummary:
The defendant was charged with both OWI (4th w/in 5 yrs) and Operating w/ PAC (4th w/in 5 yrs). The defendant was found guilty of OWI (4th w/in 5 yrs) and the other charge, Operating w/ PAC (4th w/in 5 yrs) was dismissed by the court.

  • Johnny James Young was found guilty of OWI (4th w/in 5 yrs), a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: Fine $2527.00 - to be paid during probation.
Submit DNA sample and pay $250.00 surcharge.

Not allowed to possess firearms.  Not allowed to vote or sit on a jury until civil rights are restored.    Absolute sobriety to include no purchase, possession or consumption of alcohol or controlled substances unless prescribed by a physician and then only according to physician's orders.  Probation agent also needs to approve any prescriptions.    May not be in taverns or bars or on any premises licensed for the sale of intoxicating beverages, except restaurants and grocery stores.  Not to operate any motor vehicles without a valid DL.

Defendant must complete 25 hours of community service each week by doing one of the three:   attending schooling, counseling assessments as recommended by the agent or community service.  Once defendant gets a job he only needs to perform 10 hours of community service each week.  Defendant must do random drug/alcohol tests given by the agent - defendant ordered to pay for the testing.    Enter into, participate in and successfully complete any assessments, evaluations and/or treatment programs as directed by the agent.    If defendant does not pay the fines, costs, service fees and restitution, that is to be deemed a violation such that probation should be revoked and the defendant then serves the jail sentence.
